This paper studies the query complexity of a game, which is a problem in computational complexity theory. The problem involves binary strings and permutations, which are common topics in algorithms and data structures (cs.DS) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The study of games and puzzles is also related to computational game theory (cs.GT). Additionally, the problem originates from black-box optimization heuristics, which is a topic in numerical optimization and evolutionary algorithms (cs.NE). Finally, the use of upper and lower bounds suggests a connection to computational complexity theory (cs.CC).
